</td><td><img src="/images/datel.gif" width=46 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dateblnk.gif" width=100 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dater.gif" width=306 height=22 border=0></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td>
	


		<td valign=top width=452><table cellspacing="4" cellpadding="6" width=100% border=0><tr><td background="/images/newsback.gif"><CENTER><H3><FONT FACE="ARIAL" color="#CB723D">True</FONT></H3></CENTER>
			
		<b>Level:</b> 7<br>

		<b>Race:</b> Half-Elf<br>

		<b>Class:</b> Rogue<br>

		<b>PvP Switch:</b>  Off<br>
		
		<center><h4>History:</h4></center>  <br>	Born into hatred, the child had no chance at a happy life.  He was concieved in fear and was never wanted.  Not only was he born a bastard, but he was born the son of a rapist.  His Wood Elf mother, Sylvin, was out in the forests of Faydark when she was beaten and raped by a Human mercenary.  She became pregnant with his child and so came into the world True, the product of a horrible crime.<p>	True was never wanted by his mother, she looked upon him with disgust.  Not only was he the son of the man that raped her, but he looked different than all of the other Elven children.  He was part human, a Half Elf, or as the townfolk called him: Half Breed.  For as long as long as he could remember, True was surrounded in insults and neglect.  Never having known kindness or love, he grew into a dark, angry child and constantly fought with the Wood Elf children, always beating them because of his larger size.  He was the freak of Kelethin, and at the age of twelve he was abandoned by his mother and was banished from the city to go fend for himself in the wilds of the Faydark.<p>	Luckily, not only was True strong, but he was intelligent as well.  He knew that to live amongst the beasts of the Faydark he had to become a beast himself.  Powered by his anger, True learned to hunt the wolved, bats and giant hornets of the region.  He got the supplies he needed off of the the bodies of those unlucky enough to get lost in the great woods.  He became extraordinarily well at hiding himself from the beasts he could not kill, mainly the Orcs of the region.  And from the Orcs he learned how to transform his rage into power, his power into violence.  Watching from the treetops, True regularily saw the Orcs attack and murder many Elves of the region.  He learned from watching them.  But he also realized that he was not blessed with the great strength of the Orcs, and therefore could not charge headlong into battle like they did.  He learned to stalk his prey, to wait for the right moment and then strike from the shadows.  And so he lived until the age of seventeen, when he decided it was time to comfront his past.  Slowly, True turned and began walking towards the city of Kelethin.<p>	As he waited for the lift up to town, True saw he was being stared at by the Elves around him.  He heard the words “Is that...” and “He is alive...” whispered among them and even heard someone whisper “The Half Breed has returned.”  Fire began to burn in True’s eyes and his anger caught spark.  But he did not ignite, opting instead to let them gawk at him.  And so he made his way through Kelethin until he reached the uppermost platforms of the city and his old home.<p>	Standing in front of the door, True did not know what to expect to find behind it.  Still hurt by his abandonment, he almost wished that his mother would take him back and show him the love he had never known.  Slowly the door opened to reveal a dishevel middle aged woman with a long face and the look of defeat in her eyes.<p>	“Who are you, what do you want?” she hissed, not recognizing True.<p>	“Are you so blind as to not recognize your own son, mother?” he asked, hurt at not being recognized.<p>	She looked dumbfounded for a minute before her eyes opened wide in fear and panic.<p>	“No!  That can’t be you.  Your dead.  I left you for dead.  I prayed for your death!” she screamed, slamming the door in his face.<p>	Her final words bit into him like a deep, mortal wound.  His animal instincts took over, quickly transforming his anger into power like he had learned to do in his past.  Seeing the door slammed in his face, True charged, throwing his body at it and knocking it inward.  His mother screamed upon seeing him burst in and became frantic.  Sprinting past True and out the door, she ran, wild eyed and crying out in fear.<p>	“Mother, stop running away from me!” True begged, genuine hurt in his voice.  “I’m your son mother!   I need you!”<p>	But so shocked and frightened was his mother she was oblivious to his words and blind to the drop ahead of her.  And just like she was there, she vanished.  Her screams stopped and it was quiet for a second then came a sickening thud.  An eerie silence settled over the scene as it took the shocked True a few moments to fully comprehend what had just happened.<p>	To stunned to speak, True made his way to the edge of the platform and looked down at the ground below.  The site that greeted him would forever be branded into his mind.  His mother lay broken on the ground below, her neck twisted in a perverse angle.  One arm was bent broken behind her back.  She looked like a ragdoll tossed aside by a child.  A haze set over True’s eyes and a fog blanketed his mind.  He had killed his mother.  Intentionally - no.  But because of his arrival she now lay dead on the ground below.  Through his grief, True could not hear the people screaming murderer and devil at him.  Demon and animal.  He could not hear the sound of footsteps as a guard ran at him.  Nor could he see he hilt of the sword rushing at his head.  All he could see was his mother, broken and cold.<p>	“I killed her.  I killed her...”<p>	The hilt came down and True slumped to the ground without a sound.<p>	Darkness...<br>	<br>	The smell of dank mildew entered his noise and True stirred.  Moving his hands he heard the sound of chains clinking.  Pain.  His head throbbed and dried blood caked his hair and coated his face.  Opening his eyes, True saw painful red spots and the pain in his head exploded.  Slowly the spots faded and his environment began to take shape.  A dingy ceiling of stone blocks was overhead.  Turning to his right he saw the bars and realized where he was.  Prison.  True groaned and looked at the rest of his cell.  To his suprise he realized he wasn’t alone.  Two other people were in the cell with him.  A young Elven man and an Elven woman that bore an extreme resemblence to True’s mother.  Trying to get his hands behind him to stable himself, True realized that he was was shackled at the wrists.  Then True heard a voice.<p>	“Well, it looks like the mother killer finally woke up.”<p>	True turned and saw the words were coming from the male Elf in the cell.<p>	“Well, what do you have to say for yourself, you demented freak?”<p>	“...”<p>	True was silent but the rage he had known his entire life began to surface.<p>	“Come on bastard.  Can you speak, or is that to hard for a Half Breed like you?” the Elf continued.<p>	Half Breed.  The word cut into him and brought back all the mocking and insults of his childhood.  The rage was fueled and threatened to explode.  FIre burned in True’s eyes.<p>	“Well answer me one question.” the Elf taunted.  “Did it feel good?  Well did it?  Did it feel good to kill your mother?  Did you enjoy seeing her fall and break?  Well did you!?  Did you, you sick bastard!?”<p>	Snap.  Just like that Tue changed.  No longer was he a person.  He was an animal.  Exploding to his feet, he charged the Elf, knocking him onto his back.  The Elf let out a scream of suprise and raised his hands to block the incoming blows.  True raised the chains and lock that bound his hands high above his head and then slammed them down on the Elf’s head.  A low crunch followed.  Over and over, True raised his arms and dropped, raised and dropped, raised and dropped.  Release.  Justification.  Justification for his life.  Justification for the rape.  Justification for his birth.  Justification for being a Half Breed.  Justification for his abandonment.  Justification for killing his mother.  Justification for being alive.  Justification for being himself.<p>	The Elf’s blood covered True.  He resembled a beast ripping the life from it’s prey.  The Elven woman screamed and threw herself at the bars of the cell.<p>	“Help me!  Please God help me!”<p>	True turned his head and focused his attention on the Elven woman.  The Elven man was long dead.  It looked as if a large rock had been had been dropped on his face.  The Elven woman turned and faced True, a look of pure terror in her eyes.  True, in his animal state, did not see her as the Elf he shared the cell with, but saw her as his mother.  She looked very much like her and that was to be her undoing.<p>	“You!  It was because of you that I am who I am!” True screamed, delirious in his fury.  “You abandoned me!  You abandoned me when you were all that I had!  You wanted me to die because I wasn’t like the other children!  Well, you want to see death?  You want to see death, mother?  I’ll show you death!”<p>	The Elven woman went silent, pushing herself against the bars of the cell.  The horror in her eyes could never have been copied.<p>	True ran at her, unconrolled in his rage.  The Elf looked into his eyes and saw within what could only have been described as pure Hell.  Wild and merciless.  Tormented and insane.  And then he was upon her.  Her death was quick.  Taking her head in his hands, True jerked harshly to the left and the fragile neck snapped.  The Elf jerked once and then went limp.  True released her and she crumbled to the floor.  He knelt down next to her, his mouth near her ear, and True whispered to her - <p>	“Now you see mother.  Now you see what death is.  Oh yes mother.  Now you see what I am.”<p>	Slowly the fire began to die, the rage subside.  True began to leave his animal state and return to his Half Elf self.  FInally, the fire burned out.<p>	True looked around foggy eyed, as if seeing his surroundings for the first time.  Reaching out to touch the Elven woman on the ground in front of him, True reeled back in shock and disgust.  Blood!  His hands were covered in blood, as were his clothes, his hair, his face.  He turned around to look behind him and saw what used to be the Elven man.<p>	“Oh my God...what in Hell...” True whispered at the sight of the man and the bloody stump that used to be his head.  Then he turned again to see the dead woman crumpled on the floor.  It was then that it hit him.  He had done this, he had killed them.  True had lived a life that many people would consider impossible to live through.  He had killed many things in his seventeen years.  But never had he killed another person, at least not directly.  He held himself responsible for the death of his mother, but he did not physically push her off the platform.  He *had* killed the two Elves, he had crushed one’s head and broken one’s neck.  With his hands he had ended their life.  He stood there, alone and overwhelmed.  He wanted to feel bad for the murders he had just commited.  They presented him no  threat, yet he killed them.  That was wrong, he kept trying to convince himself, but in the back of his mind he knew that as much as he hated to admit it, he enjoyed killing those people.  He liked watching them suffer and die.  The animal inside him not only craved blood and violence, it demanded it.  And when it wanted to be released, any little spark could ignite the fire.  So the Elven man found out through his tauntings.  True stood there and pondered.  Where do I stand now?<p>	Still trying to make light of the new discovery he had just made about himself, True didn’t hear the guard sneaking up behind him.  So deep in thought he was, he didn’t even hear the guard open the cell door.  But he did hear the metallic sound of the guards sword being drawn from it’s scabard.  Acting on instinct, True threw himself to the right, hearing the loud clang of the sword hitting the stone floor behind him.  Turning to face his opponent, True was wary but unafraid.  In fact, he relaized, he enjoyed it.  He enjoyed the struggle, and eventually, the kill.  And if it were to be him on the wrong end of the sword, what did it matter?  It wasn’t as if True valued the cruel joke that was his life.  In many ways, death seemed inviting.  But the animal inside him would not let him die.  It wanted only to kill and how could it do that if it was the one killed?  Looking into the guards eyes, True saw what used to be exitement replaced by fear.  Somehow the guard knew that True was not afraid of him.  He knew that True was beyond caring about himself, and that is when a man is most dangerous.  Smiling a semi-crazed smile, True launched himself at the guard, using his larger size as an advantage.  It was a risky manuever, and falling on the guard’s sword was a definite threat, but True was successful.   He slammed the shackled into the guards face, making him stumble backwards and kocking the sword free.  Lunging towards it, True found grabbed the sword and redied it.  Fire burned in his eyes as the animal knew deah was near.<p>	“Please,” the guard begged, ashen faced and pathetic.  “Please.”<p>	“Would you have spared me if I had begged please?” True asked coldly, calm and cruel.<p>	“...”<p>	The guard had no answer, he was trapped.<p>	“So be it.” True smiled, raising the sword high into the air and and carving it down in a smooth, swift arc.  It cut deep into the guards side, nearly passing through him.  A small groan broke free and then the guard exhaled one last time and crashed to the floor.<p>	Acting quickly, True grabbed the guards keys and unlocked his shackles.  And then he ran.  He ran from the cell and the horror within.  He from the dungeun and out of the prison.  He ran across the platforms and bridges of Kelethin, and the memories of his past.  And still he ran.  Deep into the Faydark he ran and he never stopped.  <p>	True still runs.  He runs from his memories, his mother, the Elves.  He lives his life deep in the Faydark, preying on those unlucky enough to cross his path.  He does not kill out of malice, he kills out of revenge.  Revenge for all the things that had wronged him.  Revenge for being born into such misery.  Killing others helped fill the void he had known all his life.  Taking their joy away made True feel better about his lack of it.  And still he roams, wild and mad.  His mind twisted, his soul corrupted beyond help.  So much hatred was all that he had known, that he now must live the nighmare that is his birthright.
<p><p>
		
